Historical Note

The National Legion of Decency was an organization founded to combat objectionable content in motion pictures from the point of view of the Roman Catholic Church in the United States. It was founded in 1933 by John T. McNicholas, Archbishop of Cincinnati, as the Catholic Legion of Decency in response to an address given by Apostolic Delegate Archbishop Amleto Giovanni Cicognani at the Catholic Charities Convention in New York City. Cicognani had warned against the role movies had against youthful innocence and urged a campaign to purify the film industry. Though established by Roman Catholic bishops, the Legion originally included many Protestant and even some Jewish clerics. For the first couple of decades of its existence, the Legion was very influential in the American motion picture industry. Their influence stemmed from the popularity of their rating system (see below), their lobbying prowess, and their circulation of a pledge (also below) in church services. The Legion suffered a setback, however, in 1952 when the Supreme Court of the United States (SCOTUS) ruled that sacrilege is not a valid ground for censorship in the U.S. The case related to Roberto Rossellini's short film Il Miracolo (Italian, 1948) that depicted St. Joseph taking sexual advantage of a young, mentally challenged peasant woman. This movie outraged the Legion and other Catholics organizations when released in the U.S. and had been banned in New York until the case was appealed to the SCOTUS.

By the 1960s, the organization had become exclusively Catholic and was renamed the National Catholic Office for Motion Pictures. Eventually, the entity was subsumed into the United States Catholic Conference (known since 2001 as the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops) Communications Department, with a further name change to the Office of Film and Broadcasting (OFB). There was also a related National Catholic Office for Radio and Television (NCORT) that went under about 1990. The OFB carried on the rating of movies (and some other media) using the system created by the National Legion of Decency (see below). Where the Legion had a broad mandate for not only rating movies, but also lobbying for movie censorship as well, the OFB began with the intention to review and rate every motion picture in the United States. It was toward this end that the OFB labored for nearly 45 years. Unfortunately, around 2005 a string of controversies arose due to reviews coming from the OFB. In particular, reviews and ratings for the movies Brokeback Mountain and The Golden Compass were met with hostility from the OFB's readership. Eventually, in 2010, the USCCB reorganized and placed the movie rating functions under the auspices of the Catholic News Service, its primary circulating agency, effectively bringing the Office of Film and Broadcasting to a close.

The rating system was generally more conservative than the Motion Picture Association of America's Production Code. Films were rated as follows: A: Morally unobjectionable B: Morally objectionable in part C: Condemned by the Legion of Decency The A rating was later divided: A-I: Suitable for all audiences A-II: Suitable for adults; later - after the introduction of A-III - suitable for adults and adolescents A-III: Suitable for adults only

The original pledge from 1933: "I wish to join the Legion of Decency, which condemns vile and unwholesome moving pictures. I unite with all who protest against them as a grave menace to youth, to home life, to country and to religion. I condemn absolutely those salacious motion pictures which, with other degrading agencies, are corrupting public morals and promoting a sex mania in our land. … Considering these evils, I hereby promise to remain away from all motion pictures except those which do not offend decency and Christian morality." Revised pledge in 1934: "I condemn all indecent and immoral motion pictures, and those which glorify crime or criminals. I promise to do all that I can to strengthen public opinion against the production of indecent and immoral films, and to unite with all who protest against them. I acknowledge my obligation to form a right conscience about pictures that are dangerous to my moral life. I pledge myself to remain away from them. I promise, further, to stay away altogether from places of amusement which show them as a matter of policy."

Scope and Contents

The records of the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops (USCCB) Communications Department/Office of Film and Broadcasting consists of three series.

Series 1, Review Files, ca. 1931-2010, in boxes 1-155, consists of documentation, reviews and ratings of various media, and some correspondence relating to the reviews. The first 150 boxes are film reviews that are mostly undated. While they can include some original notes and material pertaining to the reviews, the contents of each folder are not uniform. Some may contain little more than the review or rating, some contain media press guides in addition, while others contain larger amounts of unpublished information. Due to the volume of these reviews, the dates will be found on an as-needed basis to maintain the 25-year restriction on files. The remaining 5 boxes consist of television and media release reviews.

Series 2, Office Records, ca. 1939-2007, in boxes 156-196, is comprised of administrative documentation, correspondence, reference materials, publications, and other miscellaneous files related to the day to day business of the OFB and its parent, the USCCB Communication Department. Included are National League of Decency files on censorship in the media and other related subjects. In addition, these records contain meeting minutes of the Communication Department as it concerned the OFB and media.

Series 3, Audiovisual Materials, ca. 1965-1990, consists of a variety of more than 1,750 items in multiple media format, stored either loose or in unnumbered boxes. These include two (2) carousels of Kodak slides; 1075 seven and twelve inch audio tapes of church related radio addresses and programs, ca. 1960-1980; 535 U-matic (3/4 inch) tapes of church related televions shows, ca. 1975-1990; 66 16mm reel to reel films of television broadcasts, ca. 1965-1980; and 130 12 mm reel to reel film of television broadcasts released by USCCB, ca. 1965-1980, much of it from their now defunct National Catholic Office for Film and Television (NCORT). Please email archives@mail.lib.cua.edu with any questions about additional details, including access.

Series 3: Audiovisual Formats, ca. 1965-1990 (Mixed loose and boxed materials)

A variety of loose and unnumbered boxes of materials in multiple media formats. These include two (2) carousels of Kodak slides; 1075 seven and twelve inch audio tapes of church related radio addresses and programs, ca. 1960-1980; 535 U-matic (3/4 inch) tapes of church related television shows, ca. 1975-1990; 66 16mm reel to reel films of television broadcasts, ca. 1965-1980; and 130 12 mm reel to reel film of television broadcasts released by USCCB, ca. 1965-1980. Please email archives@mail.lib.cua.edu with any questions about additional details, including access.
